set.seed(123)

Question #2:

  • Apply different classification techniques (3 minimum) (incl. logistic regression, kNN, Naive Bayesion, decision tree, SVM, random forest) on this dataset to predict customer churn. Answer the following questions for each model (remember to use variable selection techniques where necessary!):

1. Random Forest

telco_rf_10_vars <- randomForest(formula = Churn ~ TotalCharges + tenure + MonthlyCharges + Contract + InternetService + TechSupport + OnlineSecurity + OnlineBackup + DeviceProtection + SeniorCitizen, data = telco_train_tbl, importance = TRUE, ntree = 50)
telco_test_tbl <- telco_test_tbl %>%
    mutate(preds = predict(telco_rf_10_vars, telco_test_tbl),
           probs = predict(telco_rf_10_vars, telco_test_tbl, type = "prob")[, 1])
telco_rf_roc <- roc(telco_test_tbl$Churn, telco_test_tbl$probs)
telco_rf_roc_plot <- plot(telco_rf_roc)

telco_rf_auc <- pROC::auc(telco_rf_roc)

The AUC is 0.8377.

telco_rf_auc

  • How confident are you in your model? How do you quantify your confidence?

I use confidence interval to quantify my confidence. The confidence interval is “95% CI: 0.8152-0.8601”, the range is small so I am confident in my model.

3. logistic regression

telco <- telco_origin
normalize <- function(x) { 
    x <- as.matrix(x)
    minAttr=apply(x, 2, min)
    maxAttr=apply(x, 2, max)
    x <- sweep(x, 2, minAttr, FUN="-") 
    x=sweep(x, 2,  maxAttr-minAttr, "/") 
    return (x)
}
telco[, c(-21)] <- normalize(telco[, c(-21)])
telco_train_test_split <- initial_split(telco, prop = 0.8)
telco_train_tbl <- training(telco_train_test_split)
telco_test_tbl <- testing(telco_train_test_split)
telco_vars_train <- telco_train_tbl[, c(-21)]
telco_vars_test <- telco_test_tbl[, c(-21)]
telco_target_train <- telco_train_tbl$Churn
telco_target_test <- telco_test_tbl$Churn
telco_logistic_lasso <- cv.glmnet(x = as.matrix(telco_vars_train), y = telco_target_train, alpha = 1, family="binomial")
plot(telco_logistic_lasso)

plot(telco_logistic_lasso$glmnet.fit, "lambda", label = T)

coef(telco_logistic_lasso, telco_logistic_lasso$lambda.min)

4. KNN

telco <- telco_origin
telco_train_test_split <- initial_split(telco, prop = 0.8)
telco_train_tbl <- training(telco_train_test_split)
telco_test_tbl <- testing(telco_train_test_split)

telco_train_scaled <- data.frame(scale(telco_train_tbl[, c(top.predictors)]))
telco_test_scaled <- data.frame(scale(telco_test_tbl[, c(top.predictors)]))
df <- data.frame(scale(telco_train_tbl[, c(top.predictors, "Churn")]))
df$Churn <- as.factor(df$Churn)

ctrl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", repeats = 3)
knnFit <- train(Churn ~ ., data = df, method = "knn", trControl = ctrl, preProcess = c("center","scale"), tuneLength = 20)
importance <- varImp(knnFit, scale = F)
plot(importance)

plot(knnFit)

lift_tbl <- telco_test_tbl[, c("P_TEST", "Churn")]
lift_tbl <- lift_tbl %>% arrange(desc(P_TEST))
head(lift_tbl)
##      P_TEST Churn
## 1 0.8320505     1
## 2 0.8193696     1
## 3 0.8158265     1
## 4 0.8144870     1
## 5 0.8111380     1
## 6 0.8097215     1
baserate <- mean(telco_test_tbl$Churn)
baserate
## [1] 0.2496444
n_test <- length(telco_test_tbl$Churn)
ax <- 1
ay_base <- baserate
ay_pred <- lift_tbl$Churn[1]

for (i in 2:n_test) {
    ax[i]=i
    ay_base[i]=baserate*i
    ay_pred[i]=ay_pred[i-1]+lift_tbl$Churn[i]
}
df=cbind(lift_tbl,ay_pred,ay_base)
df[1:20,]

  • Based on the totality of your analysis, how would you hypothetically suggest deploying this if you were working for this telco company?

Answer:

Since our sensitivity is always larger than specificity, which means our model has better performance on the “No Churn” customers, I would hypothetically suggest that focus more on the customers whose prediction result of churn is “No”.
